        "scripture_reference": "Gen 12:6; Gen 33:18; Gen 35:4; Gen 37:12; Gen 37:13; Gen 37:14; Josh 17:7; Josh 20:7; Josh 21:21; Josh 24:1; Josh 24:25; Josh 24:32; Judg 8:31; Judg 9:1; Judg 9:2; Judg 9:3; Judg 9:6; Judg 9:7; Judg 9:18; Judg 9:20; Judg 9:23; Judg 9:24; Judg 9:25; Judg 9:26; Judg 9:28; Judg 9:31; Judg 9:34; Judg 9:39; Judg 9:41; Judg 9:57; Judg 21:19; 1 Kgs 12:1; 1 Kgs 12:25; 1 Chr 6:67; 1 Chr 7:28; 2 Chr 10:1; Ps 60:6; Ps 108:7; Jer 41:5; Hos 6:9; Acts 7:16;",
        "description": "An ancient city linked with Nablus or, more precisely, with nearby Tell Balata. (Ps 60:6; 108:7; PICTURE, Vol. 1, p. 530) Situated at the E end of the narrow valley running between Mount Gerizim and Mount Ebal, Tell Balata lies about 48 km (30 mi) N of Jerusalem. A good supply of water is available, and just E of the site there is a fertile plain. Anciently Shechem commanded the E-W and N-S roads traversing central Palestine. (Compare Jg 21:19.) Lacking the military advantage of being built on a mountain, the city depended on its fortifications for security.​—Jg 9:35.  When Abram (Abraham) first entered the Promised Land, he traveled as far as “the site of Shechem” and encamped near the big trees of Moreh, where he later built an altar. (Ge 12:6-9) Nearly two centuries afterward Jacob, upon returning from Paddan-aram, pitched camp in front of Shechem and purchased some land there. In reaction to their sister Dinah’s being violated by Shechem the son of Hamor, the sons of Jacob​—Simeon and Levi—​killed the men of the city. ",
